A [[UFC Heavyweight Championship]] bout between former champion (also a former two-time [[UFC Light Heavyweight Championship|UFC World Light Heavyweight Champion]]) [[Jon Jones]] and former two-time world champion [[Stipe Miocic]] headlined this event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2024/09/ufc-309-news-jon-jones-vs-stipe-miocic-new-york-full-card-announced|title=Jon Jones vs. Stipe Miocic title fight headlines UFC 309 in New York|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday|author=Nolan King|date=2024-09-14|access-date=2024-09-15}}</ref> They were previously expected to headline [[UFC 295]] last November, but Jones withdrew due to a [[pectoral muscle]] injury.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4997740/2023/10/25/jon-jones-injury-ufc-295-stipe-miocic/|title=Jon Jones' UFC 295 fight vs. Stipe Miocic off due to pectoral injury: How big of a blow is this?|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Greg Rosenstein|date=2023-10-25|access-date=2024-09-18}}</ref> Interim champion at the time and current undisputed champion [[Tom Aspinall]] served as backup and potential replacement for this fight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2024/09/ufc-309-dana-white-tom-aspinall-jon-jones-vs-stipe-miocic|title=Dana White confirms Tom Aspinall as UFC 309 main event backup fighter|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Nolan King and Ken Hathaway|date=2024-09-17|access-date=2024-09-23}}</ref>

A five-round lightweight rematch between former [[UFC Lightweight Championship|UFC World Lightweight Champion]] [[Charles Oliveira]] and former three-time [[List of Bellator MMA champions#Lightweight World Championship|Bellator World Lightweight Champion]] (also a former UFC world lightweight title challenger) [[Michael Chandler]] took place as the co-main event.<ref name="Rematch">{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2024/09/ufc-309-michael-chandler-rematch-charles-oliveira-msg-conor-mcgregor-fight-possible-later|title=UFC 309: Michael Chandler to rematch Charles Oliveira in return; may fight Conor McGregor later|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Matthew Wells and Mike Bohn|date=2024-09-13|access-date=2024-09-13}}</ref> The pairing previously met for the vacant championship at [[UFC 262]] in May 2021 which Oliveira won by second-round TKO.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/ufc-262-live-results-michael-chandler-vs-charles-oliveira-highlights-results-and-analysis-223035728.html|title=UFC 262 full results: Oliveira TKOs Chandler for lightweight title|publisher=sports.yahoo.com|author=Staff|date=2021-05-15|access-date=2024-09-13}}</ref>

A welterweight bout between [[Randy Brown (fighter)|Randy Brown]] and [[Carlos Prates]] was scheduled for this event.<ref>{{Cite web|title=With an eye on the top-15, Carlos Prates seeks fourth UFC victory in November|url=https://agfight.com/ufc/de-olho-no-top-15-carlos-prates-busca-quarta-vitoria-no-ufc-em-novembro/|date=2024-10-03|access-date=2024-10-03|publisher=agfight.com|author=Diego Ribas}} {{in lang|pt-br}}</ref> However, Prates ended up being scheduled to headline [[UFC Fight Night: Magny vs. Prates]] against [[Neil Magny]] a week earlier.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2024/10/10/24267163/neil-magny-carlos-prates-ufc-vegas-100-main-event|title=Neil Magny vs. Carlos Prates set for UFC Vegas 100 main event|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Guilherme Cruz|date=2024-10-10|access-date=2024-10-10}}</ref>

A lightweight bout between [[Maurício Ruffy]] and Charlie Campbell was scheduled for this event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2024/10/ufc-309-fight-news-charlie-campbell-vs-mauricio-ruffy|title=UFC 309 adds Charlie Campbell vs. Mauricio Ruffy|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Nolan King|date=2024-10-07|access-date=2024-10-07}}</ref> However, Campbell withdrew from the fight for unknown reasons and was replaced by James Llontop.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2024/10/ufc-309-news-mauricio-ruffy-vs-charlie-campbell|title=Mauricio Ruffy once again without opponent for UFC 309 after Charlie Campbell withdraws|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Nolan King|date=2024-10-23|access-date=2024-10-23}}</ref><ref name="Llontop in">{{Cite web|author=Guilherme Cruz|date=2024-10-29|title=Mauricio Ruffy gets new opponent for UFC 309|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2024/10/29/24283241/mauricio-ruffy-gets-new-opponent-for-ufc-309|access-date=2024-10-30|publisher=mmafighting.com}}</ref> The pairing was also changed to a catchweight bout of 165 pounds.<ref>{{Cite web|author=Nolan King|date=2024-11-14|title=Two UFC 309 fight card changes announced|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2024/11/ufc-309-fight-card-jones-vs-miocic-updates|access-date=2024-11-14|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com}}</ref> Llontop weighed in 1.2 lbs over the 165 lb catchweight limit and was fined 20 percent of his purse, which went to Ruffy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/mma/news/ufc-309-weigh-results-jon-jones-stipe-miocic/128c629bd2bccfcdacbb11f5|title=UFC 309 weigh-in results: Jon Jones a little lighter, Stipe Miocic a little heavier for heavyweight title clash|publisher=sportingnews.com|author=Simon Head|date=2024-11-16|access-date=2024-11-16}}</ref>

On November 6, two fighters pulled out of the event: [[Azamat Murzakanov]], who was scheduled to face [[Nikita Krylov]] in a light heavyweight bout, withdrew for unknown reasons; and Lucas Almeida, who was expected to face [[David Onama]] at featherweight, withdrew due to medical issues.<ref>{{Cite web|author=Nolan King|date=2024-11-06|title=Two UFC 309 fighters withdraw in week prior to Madison Square Garden event|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2024/11/ufc-309-fight-card-new-york-madison-square-garden-murzakanov-almeida|access-date=2024-11-06|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com}}</ref> Almeida was replaced by promotional newcomer Roberto Romero in a lightweight bout and no replacement was found for Krylov.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2024/11/13/24295526/ufc-309-fight-card-finalized-with-13th-fight-now-complete|title=UFC 309 fight card finalized with 13th fight now complete|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Alexander K. Lee|date=2024-11-13|access-date=2024-11-13}}</ref>

A middleweight bout between former [[UFC Middleweight Championship|UFC Middleweight Champion]] [[Chris Weidman]] and former [[Legacy Fighting Alliance#LFA Middleweight Championship|LFA Middleweight Champion]] [[Eryk Anders]] was expected to take place at the event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Chris-Weidman-vs-Eryk-Anders-Booked-for-UFC-309-on-Nov-16-194568/amp|title=Chris Weidman vs. Eryk Anders booked for UFC 309 on Nov. 16|publisher=sherdog.com|author=Tristen Critchfield|date=2024-08-07|access-date=2024-11-16}}</ref> However, Anders withdrew on the day of the event because of food poisoning the night before and the bout was scrapped.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2024/11/ufc-309-chris-weidman-eryk-anders-cancellation|title=UFC 309 loses Chris Weidman vs. Eryk Anders minutes before event|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Nolan King|date=2024-11-16|access-date=2024-11-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bjpenn.com/mma-news/eryk-anders/eryk-anders-issues-statement-following-ufc-309-bout-cancellation-there-was-no-way-i-would-have-been-able-to-go-out-there/|title=Eryk Anders issues statement following UFC 309 bout cancellation: 'There was no way I would have been able to go out there'|publisher=bjpenn.com|author=Fernando Quiles|date=2024-11-17|access-date=2024-11-17}}</ref> The bout was later rescheduled for [[UFC 310]] in a 195 lb catchweight bout.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2024/11/ufc-310-chris-weidman-eryk-anders-rebooked-december-catchweight|title=UFC squeezes Chris Weidman vs. Eryk Anders rebooking onto 2024 schedule|publisher=mmajunkie.usatoday.com|author=Nolan King|date=2024-11-20|access-date=2024-11-20}}</ref>

